French Prime Minister Bayrou hands in resignation
description: François Bayrou will continue to handle day-to-day affairs until a successor is appointed. This person will be the fifth head of government since the start of Emmanuel Macron's second five-year term in 2022.

headline: Israeli army strikes Hamas officials in Qatar
description: Qatar announced that Israeli strikes targeted Hamas leaders' homes in a 'cowardly' attack. Israel's military confirmed the strikes, and Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's office said 'Israel takes full responsibility.'

headline: Le Pen, facing electoral ban, gets expedited appeal trial
description: A Paris court has scheduled the appeal trial for her party's fake assistant jobs at the European Parliament case from January 13 to February 12, 2026. The far-right Rassemblement National criticized the timing for coming just weeks before the municipal elections.

headline: Pigs heads found in front of mosques in Paris region
description: The rector of the Grand Mosque of Paris denounced the 'Islamaphobic acts' as 'a new and sad stage in the rise of anti-Muslim hatred' on Tuesday.

headline: Macron, a vulnerable president after one dissolution and two failed governments
description: The fall of Prime Minister François Bayrou ushers in a new period of political instability. The French president, widely seen as responsible for the crisis within his own ranks, now faces pressure from the opposition to propose a new candidate for the post of prime minister.

Did Macron really add €1 trillion to France's national debt?
description: While this figure often cited by opposition parties is misleading, France's debt has risen significantly under Emmanuel Macron's presidency, partly due to his tax policy decisions.

headline: Fashion retreats from diversity: 'We are again being openly asked for Caucasian models'
description: Until recently, the industry enthusiastically embraced the major social issues stirring society. From supporting Pride to Black Lives Matter, to championing inclusivity in the representation of bodies and identities, fashion seemed in tune with the times. But the tide has turned. The election of Donald Trump, who issued a series of anti-diversity executive orders, has changed everything.

headline: France's best art exhibitions this fall, in Paris and beyond
description: Here is Le Monde's selection of must-see art exhibitions, from painter John Singer Sargent to medieval forgeries to contemporary Nigerian artist Otobong Nkanga, which will go on display through the end of the year.
